    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so it's basically like a holding pen for the money so no one gets ripped off? who is usually the one in charge of that account, like is it the bank or a lawyer or something? and how do they make sure the money actually gets to the right person at the end?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, that's a great way to think about it! The escrow account is often managed by a Title Company or an Escrow Agent, not typically a bank or lawyer. They act as the neutral third party ensuring that the funds are properly managed and only released when all the conditions of the sale are fulfilled. They have a secure system in place, which usually involves an electronic transfer of funds from the buyer to the escrow account upon signing a purchase agreement. Then, once the seller's conditions are met, such as receiving the full purchase price and any other agreed-upon terms, the funds are released from the escrow account to the seller. This ensures that both parties are protected and that the funds go to the right places in a timely and secure manner.",
